keywords waystone circle charter passage
---
The Waystone Circle is the twelve-stone legal ring surrounding the Great Oasis, associated with the Charter of Passage tradition established during the Keeper of Measure era.
Each stone bears Charter of Passage inscriptions asserting that any traveler reaching the oasis by recognized route has an absolute right to draw water in the amount specified by their caravan charter.
The right inscribed on the waystones was absolute and self-executing: it could not be denied by any authority, including the Water Court itself.
Charter alteration or waystone destruction was the most serious crime in Keeper law, treated as an attack on the entire road network's legitimacy.
The stones are positioned at intervals corresponding to the primary approach routes to the oasis from each cardinal direction, serving both as legal markers and as navigational waypoints.
Each stone also functioned as a shadow-gnomon aligned for local-noon measurement, calibrated against the oasis basin's central gnomon stone to maintain the Keeper's continental survey reference network.
The twelve-stone count corresponds to the twelve recognized routes in the Keeper road system, one stone for each authorized approach.
Some waystones along the Kiess-Midgaard corridor carry carved district names of Evermeet's lost outer wards — a memorial practice the Kiess founders adopted when they established their own waystone network along the Roc Road approaches.
The Waystone Circle's Charter inscriptions survive in better condition than most Keeper-era surface text because the basalt used for the oasis stones resists weathering better than the sandstone used in desert approach markers.
The Great Oasis Waystone Circle served as the template for similar stone networks at subsidiary oasis sites along the eastern road system; several satellite rings survive in partial form.
Current political dispute at the oasis concerns whether the Charter of Passage remains operative: the Dune Reavers treat the stones as territorial markers, the Jackal Synod claims the right to mediate Charter access, and the Spring Wardens assert the original Charter authority.

